MidtermProject_Predicting the houseprice of San Francisco

Xintian Li & Jingzhi Chang

October 15, 2019

1.Introduction

This project aims to predict house prices in San Francisco. In this project, we build an Ordinary Least Square model and simulate the linear relationship between house prices and related preditor variables. While training the model, we care about both accuracy and generalizability and try to make a balance between these two standards. In other words, we hope the model trained with known house prices could predict the prices of the houses never seen before in different areas of the city. The difficulty of this project is to improve the accuracy of the regression model and meanwhile avoid overfitting the training data. To improve accuracy, we collect various variables which describe different aspects of the housing features: internal characteristics, amenities around and the spatial structure. To improve generalizability, we split training set and test set and conduct cross validation. In conclusion, we find that the house prices in San Francisco are significantly related with some of the independent variables, such as property area and crimes. Moreover, house price has spatial correlation. Similar house prices tend to cluster. In general, this model performs well, but the accuracy drops when predicting houses with higher prices, which need more researches in the future.

2. Data

This project mainly use data from Open Data San Francisco (https://datasf.org/opendata/) and American FactFinder (https://factfinder.census.gov). We collect data from following three aspects to describe the houses various characteristics:

  • 1). Internal Characteristics:

    The attributes which shows the internal qualities of the house, such as the numbers of rooms, the property area, etc.

  • 2). External Amenities:

    The elements that constitutes the outside environment of the houses. We evaluate the external amenities of houses from five aspects: School, Crime, Transit, Park, and other kinds of POI(Point of Interest)

  • 3). Spatial structure:

    The attributes that reveal the spatial correlation of the houses. In this model we find that the prices tend to spatially cluster. Therefore we select elements such as the average sale price of the nearest neighbors, the neighborhood name and census tract name which the houses locate in, etc, to describe the spatial correlation.

3. Methods

The modeling process could be divided into three main parts:

1).Data Wrangling

After gathering the three aspects of data online, we cleaned them carefully. We dealt with NAs by sub-regressions. (For instances, the number of rooms has a strong correlation with the number of beds and baths. We used beds and baths to predict the missing values of rooms, and discarded beds in the final regression model.)

2).Feature Engineering

First, to process the raw amenity data, we made different scales of buffers, and calculated the number of amenities in these buffers. Second, we adjusted the forms to present different characteristics. For example, we changed the built year of houses into dummy variables and this led to a better performance of regression. Besides, we added some quadratic and cubic terms of some important variables, such as property area. Third, to avoid collinearity, we tested the impact of different variables and selected those with the strongest predictive effects, such as the number of assaults in 500-meter buffers of all the crime data.

3).Model Building

The model building process was simultaneous with feature engineering. We used OLS regression model to predict the house prices in San Francisco. To test the accuracy and generalizability, we first split the data into training and testing sets (4:1), then did cross validation to avoid overfitting.

5. Discussion

1).Effectiveness

Generally, we believe that our model is effective, for it can predict at least 75% of the variation of house price.

2).Interesting and Important Variables

There are several interesting variables. For example, we used the park-score data. The distance between a house and its nearest high-quality park (score over 90) has a negative impact on house price. The most important variables are still internal ones, and property area is the most essential of all. The relation between these internal characteristics and sale price are not often linear, so we add some quadratic and cubic terms. Besides, the average price of 5-nearest houses is also a good predictor of the house sale price.

3).Spatial differences and error analysis

The error of prediction is around $200,000 on average, about 20% of the sale prices. According to the data and model, house prices are high in the northern and middle parts of the city, and low in southern and western parts. This model does well in predict low house prices, and not satisfying in predicting luxury houses. We believe that it is possibly because the high quality of a house might be affected by more specific features such as design and historical value.

6. Conclusion

I would recommend our model to Zillow, for we have taken a lot of characteristics into account and the performance is relatively good. However, there are still several ways to promote the model. First, as the model performs poorly when predicting high-price houses, we could improve the model by conducting more eature engineering and find the variables that contribute to high house price most. Second, this model lacks sufficient theory support. For instance, the amenity conditions are based on buffers. However, we determine the scales of the buffers by our own domain experience and some minor adjustments in feature engineering. It would be better if there is a theory behind to support the choices of the range of influence. Third, the relation between house prices and other factors are not necessarily linear. Although we have already added some exponentiation of independent variables, it is arbitrary and the model maybe still not characterise the relationship very well. A more advanced algorithm will probably contribute to a better prediction.
